Goal is to evaluate whether a species is an evolutionary unit or not


## Morphological species concept

- <#gloss Morphological species concept> (or <#gloss morphospecies>:  
species are groups of organisms that look (sufficiently) different
- Useful for working with fossils
- Takes a lot of expertise and experience
- Disadvantages?
<#finalhandout
<#pause>

    - Subjective, prone to disagreements
    - Some groups look very similar but don't/can't produce viable offspring: <#gloss cryptic species>
    - Not clear how definition relates to our conceptual definition of evolutionary units

>

## Ecological species concept

- An ecological species is a set of related organisms occupying the same ecological <#gloss niche>
    - Exploit similar resources
    - Tolerate similar environments 
    - Face similar natural enemies
    - Commonly used for small things,  
particularly small *asexual* things (why?)

## Phylogenetic species concept

<#b2cols>

- A phylogenetic species is a <#gloss monophyletic group> of populations ...
    - ... that can't be divided into smaller groups
	- (this is tricky!)
- A monophyletic group is a group *defined by* a single common ancestor
    - All descendants of the ancestor must be in the group (Fig 26.2)

